                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout>Traces of ogam inscription were first noted by Macalister in 1922. However, the ogham inscription described by Macalister was dismissed by McManus. An ogham inscription seems unlikely given what's there. The roman-letter inscription consists of three lines which may have originally read horizontally or vertically. The inscription (Edwards 2007, 159) <q>is most likely to have been read vertically downwards because it consists of a variation of the 'X son of Y' formula</q> in this format. 
                                </layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote>The Latin inscription is lightly punched and consists of capitals <q>with miniscule H. The R's have short diagonal strokes which veer towards the horizontal and that in line 1 has an open loop; F is cursive and conjoined with I, which is small; A has an angle-bar; B has separate loops; the first vertical stroke of the H has been extended downwards. ...the epigraphy includes several letter forms, notably miniscule H, which suggest it is typologically late in the series.</q> (Edwards 2007, 159-161).
                                <height></height>
                            </handNote> 
                        </handDesc>
