        <body>
            <div type="edition" subtype="roman" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="pgl-Latn">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName><name>VELVOR<gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/></name>
                    <lb n="2"/><w><hi rend="ligature">FI</hi>LIA</w> 
                    <lb n="3"/><name>BROHO<gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/></name></persName>
                </ab>
                    
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <p></p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation">
                <p><foreign xml:lang="la">Velvor...</foreign>daughter of <foreign xml:lang="pgl">Broho</foreign></p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>VELVOR can be compared with VELVE, VELVALIS and VELVINNA. VELVOR[IA] is therefore a sensible reconstruction given the previous comparisons, <q>with <hi rend="italic">-o-ria</hi> being the feminine latinized equivalent of celtic <hi rend="italic">-o-rix</hi> (Edwards 2007, 161).</q> It is one of a small group commemorating women, in this case using filia 'daughter' in the nominative case. <q>BROHO is no doubt the same welsh name as BROHOMAGLI and BROHCMAIL.(Edwards 2007, 161).</q> No ogam is visible on the stone; the inscription is entirely in Latin script.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="bibliography">
                <p><bibl><ptr target="EDW2007"/>
                    <citedRange unit="page">159-161</citedRange>
                </bibl></p>
            </div>
        </body>
